/**
 * brands — long-form SEO overrides
 */
module.exports = {
  "myfather": "<p>My Father Cigars stands as one of the most respected and influential Nicaraguan brands in the modern premium cigar world. Founded by the legendary master blender José “Pepín” García, the brand embodies a deep commitment to family tradition, bold flavor profiles, and uncompromising construction. After leaving Cuba and establishing operations first in a small Miami factory (El Rey de los Habanos), Pepín and his family—son Jaime and daughter Janny—opened their flagship factory in Estelí, Nicaragua in 2009, naming it after the seminal blend Jaime created as a tribute to his father.</p>\n<p>The García family’s roots trace back to tobacco work in Cuba, where Pepín began rolling at age 11 and became a Class 8 master roller, crafting cigars for iconic brands like Cohiba and Montecristo. My Father cigars are known for their full-bodied power, complex layers of spice, earth, leather, and sweetness, often featuring Nicaraguan tobaccos grown in the volcanic soils around Estelí. Flagship lines such as Le Bijou 1922, The Judge, and Flor de las Antillas have earned multiple Cigar of the Year accolades from Cigar Aficionado, cementing the brand’s reputation for excellence. The family also produces highly regarded cigars for Tatuaje (Pete Johnson’s project), La Aroma de Cuba, and San Cristóbal, showcasing their role as a contract manufacturing powerhouse while maintaining strict quality control across their own portfolio.</p>",
  "tatuaje": "<p>Tatuaje is a cornerstone boutique brand that helped define the modern “boutique cigar” movement. Founded by Pete Johnson in close partnership with Pepín García, Tatuaje quickly gained a cult following for its powerful, well-balanced Nicaraguan blends and distinctive packaging featuring Pete’s personal tattoos as inspiration for many vitolas and names.</p>\n<p>The brand’s core lines—the Brown Label, Black Label, Reserva, and the acclaimed Serie P—showcase exceptional construction and complex flavor profiles ranging from peppery spice and earth to leather, cocoa, and baking spices. Produced primarily at the My Father factory in Estelí, Tatuaje cigars have earned consistent high scores and a devoted following among aficionados who appreciate the brand’s no-compromise approach. The collaboration between Pete Johnson and the García family remains one of the most successful and enduring partnerships in the industry, with Tatuaje continuing to release limited and special editions that push creative boundaries while staying true to its roots.</p>",
  "padron": "<p>Padrón Cigars is one of the most respected and consistent names in the premium cigar world, founded in 1964 in Miami by Cuban émigré José Orlando Padrón. After leaving Cuba following the revolution—where his family had deep tobacco roots in Pinar del Río—Orlando started with a single roller and a dream of recreating the full-flavored cigars he loved. He quickly turned to Nicaraguan tobacco, recognizing that the volcanic soils and microclimates of the Estelí region offered a profile remarkably similar to the legendary Cuban leaf.</p>\n<p>In 1970 the company relocated operations to Estelí. Despite immense challenges—including the Nicaraguan civil war, a factory fire, and U.S. embargoes—Padrón persevered and grew into a multi-generational family business now led by Jorge Padrón. The brand is famous for its no-nonsense approach: no sales force, direct relationships with retailers, and an obsessive focus on quality. The regular Padrón line, the 1964 Anniversary Series, and the ultra-premium 1926 Serie (honoring Orlando’s birth year) are all Nicaraguan puros or near-puros that deliver remarkable consistency, complexity, and aging potential. Padrón remains a benchmark for what Nicaraguan tobacco can achieve when grown, cured, and blended with generations of expertise.</p>",
  "rojas": "<p>Rojas Cigars is the boutique brand founded by Nicaraguan-Cuban-American master blender Noel Rojas. The company has quickly earned a reputation for well-crafted, flavorful cigars that honor traditional techniques while offering distinctive personality. Core lines include Guayacan (the brand’s flagship that put Noel on the map), Havana Nights, Unfinished Business, and Street Tacos.</p>\n<p>Production for Rojas is primarily handled through contract manufacturing at A.J. Fernandez’s facilities in Estelí, allowing Noel to focus on blending and quality while leveraging one of Nicaragua’s premier production operations. The brand’s story is intertwined with Noel’s personal journey and his earlier collaborative work (including the New Order of the Ages project). Rojas represents the new generation of independent blenders who are building meaningful brands through deep knowledge of tobacco, strong manufacturing partnerships, and a commitment to authenticity rather than chasing trends.</p>",
  "guayacan": "<p>Guayacan is the pioneering brand line created by Noel Rojas that established his reputation as a serious blender. The name evokes the strong, resilient wood native to the Caribbean and Central America—symbolizing the robust yet approachable character of the cigars. Guayacan features Nicaraguan tobaccos, including influences from top growing regions and farms (with noted Aganorsa connections in some accounts), delivering balanced, flavorful smokes that appeal to a wide range of palates.</p>\n<p>Rolled primarily at A.J. Fernandez facilities in Estelí, Guayacan demonstrates the strength of the modern contract manufacturing model in Nicaragua: a talented independent blender can bring a vision to life without owning a full factory. The line has been praised for its construction, value, and consistent delivery of Nicaraguan character—earth, spice, sweetness, and complexity—without overwhelming the smoker. It remains a cornerstone of the Rojas portfolio and a favorite among those seeking quality Nicaraguan cigars from an up-and-coming name.</p>",
  "warped": "<p>Warped Cigars, founded by Kyle Gellis, has become one of the most respected and influential boutique brands of the 2010s and 2020s. Known for meticulous attention to detail, historical tobacco knowledge, and a preference for traditional, non-infused Nicaraguan and other Central American tobaccos, Warped has built a loyal following with lines such as Corto, Sarto, Cloud Hopper, Futuro, Guardian, and El Oso.</p>\n<p>Many Warped cigars—particularly recent releases like Sarto and certain Gellis Family extensions—are produced at the NACSA factory in Estelí under Kyle’s close personal oversight. This hands-on approach allows Warped to highlight specific regional characteristics from Nicaragua’s volcanic soils. The brand’s success lies in its blend of old-world sensibility with modern execution, often using sun-grown or specially selected leaves that deliver expressive, terroir-driven flavor. Warped’s collaborations and limited releases are highly anticipated, and the company’s move into its own Gellis Family Cigars projects further demonstrates its commitment to vertical creativity within the Nicaraguan ecosystem.</p>",
  "joya": "<p>Joya de Nicaragua is the oldest premium cigar brand still produced in Nicaragua, with roots dating back to 1968 when it was founded as the country’s first national cigar manufacturer. The Joya de Nicaragua factory in Estelí has survived revolution, embargo, and changing markets to remain a vital part of the industry, producing both its own iconic lines (Antaño 1970, Clásico, Cinco Décadas, Joya Red, Joya Silver) and serving as a contract manufacturer for many other brands, including significant work for Dunbarton (Sobremesa) and others.</p>\n<p>The factory’s longevity and the quality of its tobacco and rolling have made it a symbol of Nicaraguan resilience and craftsmanship. Over the decades Joya has evolved from a more traditional, sometimes milder profile to include the bold, full-bodied Antaño series that helped redefine expectations for Nicaraguan cigars in the U.S. market. Today it continues to bridge the old and new eras of Nicaraguan production.</p>",
  "laranja": "<p>Laranja Reserva is a standout brand from the Espinosa family, known for its distinctive Brazilian Arapiraca wrapper combined with Nicaraguan filler and binder. Produced at the La Zona factory in Estelí, Laranja delivers a unique flavor profile—earthy, spicy, with sweet and floral notes from the wrapper—that sets it apart from more traditional Nicaraguan puros.</p>\n<p>The brand has become a favorite for those seeking something different within the Espinosa portfolio. Its success demonstrates how creative use of non-traditional wrapper tobaccos, grown and processed with care, can expand the flavor possibilities available to aficionados while still leveraging the strength and consistency of Nicaraguan core tobaccos. Laranja exemplifies the innovative spirit of the Espinosa operation.</p>",
  "knucklesandwich": "<p>Knuckle Sandwich is the high-profile collaboration between Erik Espinosa and celebrity chef Guy Fieri. Rolled at La Zona in Estelí, the cigars deliver the bold, full-bodied Nicaraguan character Espinosa is known for, wrapped in a distinctive package that reflects Guy Fieri’s larger-than-life personality.</p>\n<p>The partnership has brought significant attention to Nicaraguan cigars among a broader audience while maintaining the quality standards expected by serious enthusiasts. Knuckle Sandwich shows how strategic collaborations between established manufacturers and public figures can expand the reach of premium cigars without diluting the product. The line remains a fun yet serious entry in the Espinosa family of brands.</p>",
  "sixzeroone": "<p>601 is one of the flagship brands of Espinosa Premium Cigars and a direct descendant of the original EO Brands project. The 601 line is celebrated for its bold Nicaraguan profile, excellent construction, and approachable pricing. Produced at La Zona in Estelí, 601 has been a consistent performer and a gateway cigar for many enthusiasts entering the world of full-bodied Nicaraguan smokes.</p>\n<p>Over the years the 601 family has expanded with various wrapper and size options while staying true to its core identity. Its enduring popularity speaks to the strength of the Espinosa blending and manufacturing team and the reliability of Nicaraguan tobacco when handled with expertise. 601 remains a benchmark value in the Espinosa portfolio.</p>",
  "murcielago": "<p>Murciélago (“bat” in Spanish) is another core Espinosa brand, known for its dark, powerful aesthetic and full-bodied Nicaraguan character. Like other Espinosa lines, it is produced at the La Zona factory and offers enthusiasts a step up in intensity while maintaining the excellent construction and value that define the company.</p>\n<p>The brand’s dramatic presentation and robust flavor have made it a favorite among fans of big, unapologetic cigars. Murciélago demonstrates Espinosa’s ability to create multiple distinct identities within the same high-quality manufacturing environment, giving retailers and consumers a range of options from the same trusted source.</p>",
  "padron1964": "<p>Padrón 1964 Anniversary is the middle tier of the iconic Padrón family, honoring the year José Orlando Padrón founded the company. These Nicaraguan puros (or near-puros) are aged for years and offered in a variety of sizes and wrapper shades (Natural and Maduro). They deliver the signature Padrón consistency—rich, complex, and balanced—with slightly more refinement than the regular line but below the ultra-premium 1926 Serie.</p>\n<p>The 1964 line has been a mainstay of the Padrón portfolio for decades and remains one of the most reliable and highly regarded cigars in the industry. Its success helped establish the modern template for aged, family-owned Nicaraguan brands that prioritize quality and direct retailer relationships over mass marketing.</p>",
  "padron1926": "<p>Padrón Serie 1926 is the pinnacle of the Padrón lineup, created to honor the birth year of founder José Orlando Padrón. These are among the most carefully aged and selected cigars in the world—Nicaraguan tobaccos given extended time in the family’s vast aging rooms in Estelí before being rolled and then aged again as finished cigars. The result is a level of smoothness, complexity, and depth that few cigars achieve.</p>\n<p>The 1926 Serie is offered in limited quantities and a range of sizes, with both Natural and Maduro wrappers. It is widely considered one of the finest expressions of Nicaraguan tobacco available and a fitting tribute to Orlando’s vision. For many aficionados, a Padrón 1926 represents the pinnacle of what the Nicaraguan cigar renaissance has accomplished.</p>",
  "davidoff": "<p>Davidoff is one of the most prestigious and globally recognized names in the cigar world, with a heritage dating back to the early 20th century. While the brand has Swiss/Dominican corporate ownership through Oettinger Davidoff, it maintains significant production and sourcing ties to Nicaragua, where many of its popular lines (including the Nicaragua series) are crafted.</p>\n<p>The company’s commitment to quality, innovation, and worldwide distribution has made Davidoff a benchmark for luxury cigars. Its Nicaraguan offerings showcase the power and complexity of the region’s tobacco while meeting the exacting standards of one of the industry’s most demanding brands. Davidoff’s presence in the Nicaraguan ecosystem highlights how the country’s production capacity supports both independent boutiques and major international houses.</p>",
  "arturo": "<p>Arturo Fuente is a legendary Dominican family brand with deep roots and a growing presence in Nicaragua. The Fuente family has long been one of the most respected names in cigars, famous for OpusX, Hemingway, Don Carlos, and many other iconic lines. Their Tabacalera A. Fuente factory in the Dominican Republic is world-famous, but they have also developed significant operations and partnerships in Nicaragua.</p>\n<p>The Fuentes’ move into Nicaraguan production reflects the broader industry shift toward the region’s exceptional tobacco. Lines such as Fuente Fuente OpusX and various Hemingway and Don Carlos variants benefit from Nicaraguan leaf, while the family continues to maintain its Dominican heart. Arturo Fuente represents the highest levels of traditional craftsmanship combined with strategic use of the best tobaccos available across the Caribbean and Central America.</p>",
  "opusx": "<p>Fuente Fuente OpusX is widely regarded as one of the greatest cigars ever made and the cigar that put the Fuente family’s Nicaraguan tobacco program on the map. Originally released in the mid-1990s after years of secretive development, OpusX was the first cigar to feature a Dominican wrapper grown from Cuban-seed tobacco on the Fuente farms—an achievement many thought impossible at the time.</p>\n<p>The blend’s power, complexity, and aging potential set new standards. While primarily associated with the Dominican Republic, OpusX and related Fuente lines draw on Nicaraguan tobacco as well. The cigar remains a holy grail for collectors and a symbol of the Fuentes’ willingness to innovate at the highest levels while honoring family tradition. Its influence on the entire premium cigar category cannot be overstated.</p>",
  "sancristobal": "<p>San Cristóbal is a premium Nicaraguan brand owned by the Levin family through <a href=\"/node/ashton/\">Ashton</a> and rolled at the <a href=\"/node/myfather/\">My Father</a> factory in Estelí under the García family's supervision. The line was developed as a fuller-bodied companion to Ashton's traditionally milder Dominican portfolio, giving smokers a Nicaraguan expression with the same quality standards the Levins have demanded for decades.</p>\n<p>Core releases such as Clasico, Revelation, Quintessence, La Fuerza, and Paradiso have earned strong ratings for their balance of spice, earth, and sweetness. The brand sits at an interesting intersection of the industry map: corporate ownership through Ashton, boutique-level blending through Pepín García's operation, and a family connection to <a href=\"/node/tatuaje/\">Tatuaje</a> via Janny García and Pete Johnson's long collaboration with My Father. San Cristóbal demonstrates how a retailer-owned brand can leverage Nicaragua's best manufacturing without sacrificing identity.</p>",
  "ashton": "<p>Ashton is one of the longest-running and most respected premium cigar brands in the American market, founded by Robert Levin and now led by the Levin family. Unlike many brands that chase Nicaragua's volcanic power, Ashton built its reputation on refined, approachable profiles rolled at the legendary <a href=\"/node/arturo/\">Arturo Fuente</a> factory in the Dominican Republic—one of the most trusted manufacturing partnerships in the industry.</p>\n<p>Flagship lines including Classic, Cabinet Selection, Aged Maduro, VSG, ESG, and Symmetry span a wide range of strengths while maintaining the brand's hallmark smoothness and consistency. Ashton also owns Nicaraguan sister brands <a href=\"/node/laaromadecuba/\">La Aroma de Cuba</a> and <a href=\"/node/sancristobal/\">San Cristóbal</a>, produced at My Father in Estelí. This dual-country strategy—Dominican elegance through Fuente, Nicaraguan power through the Garcías—makes Ashton a quietly influential player across both of the industry's dominant production hubs.</p>",
  "rockypatel": "<p>Rocky Patel Premium Cigars has grown from a boutique startup in the late 1990s into one of the largest independent family-owned operations in the premium cigar world. Led by Nish Patel alongside founder Rocky Patel, the company is vertically integrated through its ownership of <a href=\"/node/tavicusa/\">Tabacalera Villa Cuba (TaviCusa)</a> in Estelí while maintaining deep manufacturing partnerships with <a href=\"/node/plasencia/\">Plasencia</a> in both Honduras and Nicaragua.</p>\n<p>Lines such as Decade, Vintage 1990, The Edge, Sun Grown, and Olde World have made Rocky Patel a household name among enthusiasts who want consistent quality across price points. The brand's scale—owning factories, sourcing tobacco across Central America, and maintaining one of the broadest portfolios in the industry—reflects the modern Nicaraguan cigar boom at its most ambitious. Rocky Patel sits alongside major producers like Oliva and Perdomo as proof that family-led companies can compete at the highest volumes without losing brand identity.</p>",
  "illusione": "<p>Illusione Cigars, founded by Dion Giolito, is a cult boutique brand prized for meticulous blending, understated packaging, and cigars that reward patience rather than flash. Giolito built Illusione in the tradition of small-batch, terroir-driven Nicaraguan cigars, relying heavily on tobacco from <a href=\"/node/aganorsa/\">Aganorsa Leaf</a> and production at TABSA in Estelí, with some lines also passing through <a href=\"/node/sanlotano/\">A.J. Fernandez's San Lotano</a> facilities.</p>\n<p>Core releases—the Original Documents, Singularé, 88, CG4, and Epernay—are known for refined structure, medium-plus to full body, and exceptional aging potential. Illusione helped define the \"quiet boutique\" aesthetic of the 2000s and 2010s: no celebrity partnerships, no infused gimmicks, just tobacco selected and fermented with obsessive care. For aficionados tracing the Aganorsa ecosystem, Illusione remains one of the most respected names on the map alongside <a href=\"/node/viaje/\">Viaje</a> and other TABSA regulars.</p>",
  "viaje": "<p>Viaje Cigars, founded by Andre Farkas, is one of the most collectible boutique brands in the modern era—famous for limited releases, creative vitolas, and blends that often sell out within hours. Farkas built Viaje on the philosophy of small batches and constant experimentation, making each release feel like an event rather than a permanent shelf fixture.</p>\n<p>Production flows through Nicaragua's top contract facilities, with frequent work at <a href=\"/node/aganorsa/\">Aganorsa</a>'s TABSA factory and the <a href=\"/node/joya/\">Joya de Nicaragua</a> factory in Estelí. Lines such as Exclusivo, Double Ligero, Placeres, Oro, and Summerfest have earned devoted followings and strong critical scores. Viaje shares the Nicaraguan production ecosystem with peers like <a href=\"/node/illusione/\">Illusione</a> and <a href=\"/node/hvc/\">HVC</a>, and its scarcity-driven model has influenced how an entire generation of boutique brands thinks about release strategy and brand mystique.</p>",
  "camacho": "<p>Camacho is a bold, unapologetic brand rooted in the Corojo tobacco tradition of Honduras and the legacy of the Eiroa family—whose influence also runs through <a href=\"/node/cle/\">CLE Cigar Company</a>. Acquired by <a href=\"/node/davidoff/\">Davidoff</a> (Oettinger Davidoff AG) in 2008, Camacho retained its identity as a powerhouse brand for smokers who want strength, spice, and attitude rather than subtlety.</p>\n<p>Core lines including Corojo, Connecticut, Triple Maduro, Broadleaf, and Ecuador cover a spectrum from classic Honduran fire to more modern wrapper experiments. Under the Davidoff corporate umbrella alongside Zino and other holdings, Camacho gives the luxury group a credible entry in the \"loud and proud\" segment of the market. The brand's history—from Christian Eiroa's ownership to its current global distribution—illustrates how Honduran Corojo heritage and corporate scale can coexist without diluting the product's core character.</p>",
  "laaromadecuba": "<p>La Aroma de Cuba is a Nicaraguan brand owned by the Levin family through <a href=\"/node/ashton/\">Ashton</a> and produced at the <a href=\"/node/myfather/\">My Father</a> factory in Estelí. The line was created to deliver exceptional value in the premium segment—combining Ashton's retail expertise and quality standards with Pepín García's blending mastery and Nicaragua's volcanic tobacco.</p>\n<p>Releases such as Original, Mi Amor, Edición Especial, Pasión, Noblesse, and Connecticut have repeatedly earned 90+ ratings, often at price points that undercut comparable boutique cigars. La Aroma de Cuba is one of the clearest examples of the modern contract model working at scale: a retailer-owned brand, a world-class factory, and tobaccos selected with the same care as far more expensive labels. It remains a gateway cigar for enthusiasts discovering Nicaraguan production through the García family's work.</p>",
  "alecbradley": "<p>Alec Bradley has built a reputation over two decades for cigars that punch above their price point—combining consistent construction, creative branding, and blends that appeal to both everyday smokers and serious enthusiasts. Founded by Alan Rubin and now part of <a href=\"/node/stg/\">Scandinavian Tobacco Group</a> following a 2023 acquisition from Forged Cigar Co., the brand maintains a distinct identity within STG's vast portfolio.</p>\n<p>Flagship lines such as Prensado, Tempus, Black Market, Magic Toast, and the Cigar of the Year series have earned critical acclaim and broad retail placement. Prensado in particular—with its Honduran Corojo wrapper—became one of the most recognized value-premium cigars of the 2010s. Alec Bradley's acquisition by STG reflects the ongoing consolidation trend in the industry, but the brand's track record of quality and accessibility keeps it relevant alongside independent boutiques and legacy corporate labels alike.</p>",
  "lapalina": "<p>La Palina is a revived historic American brand with roots dating to the 1890s, brought back to life by Bill Paley (great-grandson of the original founder Samuel Paley). The modern La Palina operates as a negociant—curating ultra-premium blends across multiple factories rather than owning a single production facility—allowing each line to be matched with the best available craftsmanship.</p>\n<p>The legendary Goldie series is rolled at <a href=\"/node/eltitandebronze/\">El Titan de Bronze</a> in Miami, while other lines are produced with <a href=\"/node/ajfernandez/\">A.J. Fernandez</a> in Estelí and at <a href=\"/node/pdr/\">PDR Cigars</a> in the Dominican Republic. Releases including El Diario, Mr. Sam, Classic, and the 125th Anniversary edition span a range of strengths and price tiers. La Palina's story—heritage brand, modern negociant model, multi-factory production—offers a different template from the vertically integrated Nicaraguan powerhouses that dominate much of the current map.</p>",
  "westtampa": "<p>West Tampa Tobacco Co. is a boutique brand founded in 2022 by Rick Rodriguez, a longtime master blender who spent years crafting CAO and other lines at <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a>, alongside partner Gus Martinez. The company name deliberately evokes Tampa's historic cigar-making heritage while focusing production in modern Nicaraguan facilities—primarily <a href=\"/node/garmendia/\">Garmendia Cigars</a> in Estelí, with some work at <a href=\"/node/nacsa/\">NACSA</a>.</p>\n<p>Lines such as White, Black, Red, the Attic Series, Circle of Life, and Dark Time deliver the bold, well-balanced Nicaraguan character Rodriguez is known for, wrapped in distinctive branding that nods to Tampa's past. West Tampa represents a familiar industry pattern: an experienced blender leaving corporate production to build an independent brand with trusted factory partners. For enthusiasts following the Estelí ecosystem, it is another example of how veteran talent continues to shape the boutique landscape.</p>",
  "avo": "<p>AVO is a premium Dominican brand created by composer and cigar enthusiast Avo Uvezian under the <a href=\"/node/oettinger/\">Oettinger Davidoff</a> luxury umbrella. Known for elegant, balanced blends—often featuring classic Cameroon wrappers—AVO cigars are rolled at <a href=\"/node/tabadom/\">Tabadom</a> in the Dominican Republic alongside other Davidoff-group production.</p>\n<p>AVO occupies the refined, approachable tier of the Davidoff portfolio: less intense than Davidoff Nicaragua, more accessible than OpusX, but held to the same corporate quality standards. For smokers exploring the Davidoff ecosystem, AVO offers a gateway to the group's manufacturing excellence without the ultra-premium price point of the flagship Davidoff lines.</p>",
  "griffins": "<p>The Griffin's is a historic Dominican brand under <a href=\"/node/oettinger/\">Oettinger Davidoff</a>, originally created in the 1960s and known for elegant, mild-to-medium profiles that appeal to smokers seeking refinement without intensity. Production takes place at <a href=\"/node/tabadom/\">Tabadom</a> in Villa González, sharing manufacturing infrastructure with <a href=\"/node/avo/\">AVO</a> and <a href=\"/node/davidoff/\">Davidoff</a> lines.</p>\n<p>As one of the older names in the Davidoff portfolio, The Griffin's represents continuity—the kind of steady, consistent brand that built the Dominican Republic's reputation for approachable premium cigars long before Nicaragua's boutique boom. It remains a quiet staple for aficionados who value balance and smoothness over power.</p>",
  "zino": "<p>Zino is a brand created in honor of Zino Davidoff himself, offering approachable, well-made cigars with strong value under the <a href=\"/node/davidoff/\">Davidoff</a> group and <a href=\"/node/oettinger/\">Oettinger Davidoff</a> corporate umbrella. Primarily produced in Honduras, Zino lines such as Zino Platinum, Zino Nicaragua, and Zino Honduras span a range of strengths while maintaining the accessible character that distinguishes the brand from ultra-luxury Davidoff offerings.</p>\n<p>Zino fills an important niche in the Davidoff portfolio: premium enough to carry the Davidoff name, approachable enough for everyday smoking. Alongside <a href=\"/node/camacho/\">Camacho</a> on the bolder end, Zino helps the group cover the full spectrum from refined elegance to unapologetic power across multiple Central American production hubs.</p>",
  "macanudo": "<p>Macanudo is one of the best-selling premium cigar brands in the United States, produced and distributed by <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a> under <a href=\"/node/stg/\">Scandinavian Tobacco Group</a> ownership. The brand built its reputation on consistent, elegant Connecticut-shade profiles that appeal to a broad audience—from casual smokers to longtime enthusiasts seeking a reliable, mild-to-medium daily cigar.</p>\n<p>Macanudo's enduring popularity demonstrates that not every successful premium brand chases Nicaraguan power or boutique scarcity. Its scale, shelf presence, and decades of consistency make it a cornerstone of the corporate side of the industry map—the accessible face of STG's vast portfolio alongside bolder siblings like <a href=\"/node/cao/\">CAO</a> and <a href=\"/node/lagloriacubana/\">La Gloria Cubana</a>.</p>",
  "cao": "<p>CAO is a bold, innovative brand founded in the 1990s and now owned by <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a> / <a href=\"/node/stg/\">STG</a>. Famous for colorful packaging, creative marketing, and full-flavored lines that pushed boundaries in the premium segment, CAO helped introduce a younger generation of smokers to cigars beyond traditional mild Dominican profiles.</p>\n<p>Long associated with master blender <a href=\"/node/rickrodriguez/\">Rick Rodriguez</a>, who spent nearly three decades as CAO's ambassador before founding <a href=\"/node/westtampa/\">West Tampa Tobacco Co.</a>, CAO's story intertwines corporate scale with individual blending talent. The brand remains a major presence in STG's portfolio—proof that innovation and mass distribution are not always mutually exclusive.</p>",
  "cohiba_nc": "<p>Cohiba (Non-Cuban) is produced under license by <a href=\"/node/forged/\">Forged Cigar Co.</a> within the <a href=\"/node/stg/\">STG</a> portfolio. It is entirely separate from the iconic Cuban Cohiba and offers Dominican and Nicaraguan blends that leverage one of the most recognized names in cigars for the non-Cuban market.</p>\n<p>The non-Cuban Cohiba line illustrates how historic brand names migrate across political boundaries and corporate ownership structures. While purists debate the use of the Cohiba name outside Cuba, the brand's retail success speaks to the power of name recognition—channeling consumer curiosity toward quality blends produced through STG's Dominican and Nicaraguan manufacturing relationships.</p>",
  "partagas_nc": "<p>Partagas (Non-Cuban) is a <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a> brand with roots in one of the most historic names in cigars—completely separate from the Cuban Partagás line. The non-Cuban version offers medium-to-full cigars made in the Dominican Republic, carrying forward a legacy name for the American and international markets where Cuban products remain embargoed.</p>\n<p>Like other heritage-name non-Cuban brands (<a href=\"/node/cohiba_nc/\">Cohiba</a>, <a href=\"/node/punch_nc/\">Punch</a>), Partagas demonstrates how STG and General Cigar preserve recognizable identities while sourcing tobacco and production from accessible Caribbean and Central American facilities. The brand serves smokers who want traditional, full-flavored profiles under a name steeped in cigar history.</p>",
  "punch_nc": "<p>Punch is a historic cigar name now produced as a non-Cuban brand under <a href=\"/node/forged/\">Forged Cigar Co.</a> and <a href=\"/node/stg/\">Scandinavian Tobacco Group</a>. The line offers traditional, full-flavored cigars blending Nicaraguan and Dominican tobaccos—carrying a brand identity that dates to the 19th century into the modern premium market.</p>\n<p>Punch's placement in the Forged/STG portfolio alongside <a href=\"/node/cohiba_nc/\">Cohiba (Non-Cuban)</a> reflects how corporate groups organize legacy brand names for U.S. distribution. For enthusiasts mapping ownership, Punch is a clear example of how iconic Cuban-associated names live on through entirely separate supply chains and manufacturing relationships.</p>",
  "lagloriacubana": "<p>La Gloria Cubana (non-Cuban) is owned by <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a> / <a href=\"/node/stg/\">STG</a> and famous for powerful, full-flavored cigars—most notably the acclaimed Serie R line. Produced in the Dominican Republic, the brand carries a historic Cuban name into the modern era with blends that appeal to enthusiasts seeking strength and complexity.</p>\n<p>La Gloria Cubana stands apart from milder STG siblings like <a href=\"/node/macanudo/\">Macanudo</a>, occupying the fuller-bodied tier of General Cigar's portfolio. Its success proves that corporate-owned brands can still deliver the intensity and character that serious aficionados demand, even when separated from the original Cuban heritage that inspired the name.</p>",
  "room101": "<p>Room101 is a bold, irreverent cigar brand with a strong cult following, known for creative branding and full-flavored blends that refuse to take themselves too seriously. Acquired by <a href=\"/node/stg/\">Scandinavian Tobacco Group</a> in 2022 (previously distributed through <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a>), Room101 represents STG's appetite for boutique-leaning brands with established enthusiast followings.</p>\n<p>The brand's journey from independent cult label to corporate portfolio mirrors broader consolidation trends in the industry—while maintaining the edgy identity that attracted fans in the first place. Room101 adds personality to STG's shelf presence alongside more traditional names like Macanudo and Partagas.</p>",
  "jcnewman": "<p>J.C. Newman Cigar Co. is America's oldest family-owned premium cigar company, founded in 1895 in Cleveland and now based in Tampa, Florida. The Newman family produces cigars in the Dominican Republic through a longtime partnership with <a href=\"/node/arturo/\">Arturo Fuente</a>—a relationship that has endured across generations and produced some of the finest ultra-premium lines in the industry.</p>\n<p>The company's flagship <a href=\"/node/diamondcrown/\">Diamond Crown</a> line, handmade at <a href=\"/node/tabafuente/\">Tabacalera A. Fuente</a>, represents the pinnacle of the Newman-Fuente collaboration. J.C. Newman embodies American cigar history: a family business that survived Prohibition, the Cuban embargo, industry consolidation, and changing consumer tastes by betting on quality partnerships rather than vertical integration alone.</p>",
  "diamondcrown": "<p>Diamond Crown is the ultra-premium flagship line of <a href=\"/node/jcnewman/\">J.C. Newman</a>, handmade at the legendary <a href=\"/node/tabafuente/\">Tabacalera A. Fuente</a> factory in the Dominican Republic. Known for exceptional quality, elegant presentation, and meticulous construction, Diamond Crown represents the highest tier of the Newman-Fuente partnership—a collaboration between America's oldest family-owned cigar company and one of the world's most respected manufacturers.</p>\n<p>With extended aging, refined blends, and vitolas designed for connoisseurs, Diamond Crown sits alongside <a href=\"/node/ashton/\">Ashton</a> and <a href=\"/node/opusx/\">OpusX</a> in the conversation about Dominican ultra-premium cigars. The line demonstrates what happens when two family dynasties combine their strengths without corporate interference diluting the result.</p>",
  "espinosahabano": "<p>Espinosa Habano is a core line from <a href=\"/node/espinosa/\">Espinosa Premium Cigars</a>, featuring a Habano wrapper over bold Nicaraguan filler and binder tobaccos. Rolled at the <a href=\"/node/lazona/\">La Zona</a> factory in Estelí, the line delivers the full-bodied character Erik Espinosa is known for—spice, earth, and richness in a profile that appeals to enthusiasts who want Nicaraguan power with excellent construction.</p>\n<p>Alongside <a href=\"/node/sixzeroone/\">601</a>, <a href=\"/node/murcielago/\">Murciélago</a>, <a href=\"/node/laranja/\">Laranja</a>, and <a href=\"/node/crema/\">Crema</a>, Espinosa Habano rounds out a diverse portfolio that lets the company reach different palate preferences while manufacturing everything under one roof. It remains a reliable expression of La Zona's blending and rolling capabilities.</p>",
  "crema": "<p>Crema is a popular line from <a href=\"/node/espinosa/\">Espinosa Premium Cigars</a>, known for a creamier, more approachable profile than the company's bolder offerings while still delivering genuine Nicaraguan flavor. Rolled at <a href=\"/node/lazona/\">La Zona</a> in Estelí, Crema serves as a gateway cigar within the Espinosa portfolio—accessible enough for newer enthusiasts, flavorful enough for seasoned smokers.</p>\n<p>Crema demonstrates Erik Espinosa's range as a blender: the same factory that produces powerhouses like 601 and Murciélago also delivers refined, smoother profiles when the blend calls for it. The line's success speaks to the importance of offering multiple entry points within a single brand family.</p>",
  "sobremesa": "<p>Sobremesa is the flagship brand of <a href=\"/node/dunbarton/\">Dunbarton Tobacco &amp; Trust</a>, created by <a href=\"/node/stevesaka/\">Steve Saka</a> and celebrated for its complexity, balance, and the convivial spirit its name evokes—\"sobremesa\" being the Spanish word for the relaxed conversation that follows a meal. Primary production takes place at the <a href=\"/node/joyafactory/\">Joya de Nicaragua factory</a> in Estelí.</p>\n<p>Sobremesa established Saka's reputation as an independent blender after his Drew Estate years, proving that thoughtful tobacco selection and exacting construction standards could create cigars that feel both traditional and modern. The brand remains one of the most anticipated and highly rated in the boutique segment—a benchmark for what contract manufacturing at a top facility can achieve when guided by a master blender's vision.</p>",
  "belladamacigars": "<p>Bella Dama Cigars is an independent, woman-owned boutique brand founded by <a href=\"/node/chantelleavitt/\">Chantel Leavitt</a> as a tribute to her late father, a professional poker player. The lineup features a distinctive poker and card-room theme across releases such as The King, Ace, The Queen, and Flush—rolled at <a href=\"/node/tabacaleraaragon/\">Tabacalera Aragon</a> in Estelí.</p>\n<p>Bella Dama represents the personal-story-driven side of the modern boutique boom: a brand built on family memory, creative branding, and partnership with a craft-oriented factory rather than industrial scale. For the map, it connects an emerging founder to Estelí's long tail of smaller rolling operations that keep the ecosystem accessible to new entrants.</p>",
  "karenberger": "<p>Karen Berger Cigars is a vertically integrated Nicaraguan brand led by <a href=\"/node/karenbergerperson/\">Karen Berger</a>, continuing the legacy of Don Kiki Cigars and producing quality Nicaraguan puros from the company's own farms and <a href=\"/node/tabacaleraesteli/\">Tabacalera Estelí</a> factory. The operation controls growing, fermentation, and rolling on-site—a farm-to-cigar model that ensures every blend reflects Berger's personal standards.</p>\n<p>Karen Berger Cigars honors the memory of Enrique \"Don Kiki\" Berger while building a family operation rooted in decades of Estelí craftsmanship. The brand may not have the global fame of Padrón or Oliva, but its owner-operator model embodies the grassroots independence that keeps Nicaragua's cigar capital diverse and vibrant.</p>",
  "domain": "<p>Domain Cigars is a vertically integrated boutique brand founded by Esteban Disla and Daniel Lance, with their own factory operation in Estelí. Lines such as Neutron, Negentropy, and Entropy reflect a scientific, conceptual branding approach paired with Nicaraguan tobaccos selected and fermented under the founders' direct oversight.</p>\n<p>Domain's owner-operator model—controlling production rather than relying solely on contract manufacturing—places it alongside <a href=\"/node/karenberger/\">Karen Berger</a> and <a href=\"/node/hvc/\">HVC</a> in the boutique-to-vertical category. The brand demonstrates that even in a market dominated by mega-factories, there is still room for small, founder-led operations with distinct identities.</p>",
  "elseptimo": "<p>El Septimo is a luxury cigar brand owned by Zaya Younan, distinguished by long-aged, high-elevation Costa Rican tobacco and artistic, collection-oriented releases. Primary production takes place at <a href=\"/node/costaricatabacos/\">Tabacos de Costa Rica</a>—anchoring the brand to a specific Costa Rican origin rather than the Nicaragua-Dominican-Honduras triangle that dominates most premium cigars.</p>\n<p>El Septimo's luxury positioning—rarity, aging discipline, presentation—represents a different template from Estelí's volcanic-powerhouse norm. For the map, the Costa Rica node broadens the industry's geographic story beyond Central America's traditional cigar capitals.</p>",
  "laaurora": "<p>La Aurora is the oldest premium cigar manufacturer in the Dominican Republic, family-owned by the León family since 1903. Cigars are rolled at the historic <a href=\"/node/laaurorafactory/\">La Aurora Cigar Factory</a>—a century-old facility that predates virtually every other active node on the map.</p>\n<p>While much of the enthusiast conversation centers on Nicaragua's boutique boom, La Aurora reminds smokers that the Dominican Republic remains a vital origin for refined, balanced profiles. The León family's multigenerational commitment mirrors the Padrón and Fuente stories, rooted in Santiago and Santo Domingo rather than Estelí.</p>",
  "definition": "<p>Definition Cigars is a boutique brand founded by Jamond Hackley, emphasizing craftsmanship, balance, and thoughtful blending. Production takes place at <a href=\"/node/lucianopichardo/\">Tabacalera Pichardo (Luciano)</a> in Estelí—lines such as GEN 413, the 919 Series, Noir, Conception, and The Pig have earned attention for construction quality and distinctive flavor profiles.</p>\n<p>Definition represents the craft-focused end of Estelí's boutique spectrum—a brand prioritizing blend integrity and roller skill over hype. For enthusiasts exploring beyond the biggest names, Definition offers a verifiable factory connection on the map.</p>",
  "lure": "<p>Lure Cigars is an independent boutique brand founded by Lou Cross III with a distinctive fishing and outdoors theme. Production is handled at <a href=\"/node/ovejanegra/\">Oveja Negra (Lanuza)</a> in Estelí—delivering approachable Nicaraguan character with branding that stands out on crowded retail shelves.</p>\n<p>Lure exemplifies the personality-driven boutique segment: a founder bringing personal passion to cigar branding while relying on Estelí's contract manufacturing infrastructure to execute the blends.</p>",
  "gurkha": "<p>Gurkha is one of the most widely distributed premium cigar brands, with Dominican production across multiple contract facilities including <a href=\"/node/williamventura/\">Tabacalera William Ventura</a> and <a href=\"/node/lacarrillo/\">Casa Carrillo</a>. Known for luxury positioning and extensive SKU breadth, Gurkha illustrates the negociant-at-scale model: a brand identity built across several rolling floors rather than a single factory.</p>\n<p>For the map, Gurkha connects mainstream retail visibility to the Dominican contract ecosystem—often rolling at facilities that also produce Viaje, Kristoff, and La Palina lines.</p>",
  "caldwell": "<p>Caldwell Cigars—Robert Caldwell's negociant-style boutique operation—spans multiple factories: <a href=\"/node/pdr/\">PDR</a> in the Dominican Republic, <a href=\"/node/nicasueno/\">Nica Sueño</a> in Estelí, and <a href=\"/node/williamventura/\">William Ventura</a>, among others. Lines such as Blind Man's Bluff, Long Live the King, Lost &amp; Found, and Eastern Standard have earned a devoted following for creative blending and storytelling.</p>\n<p>Caldwell is a textbook example of the modern negociant: match each blend to the right factory and country rather than owning one rolling floor. The map's multi-link pattern for Caldwell reflects how serious boutique brands actually operate behind the scenes.</p>",
  "crownedheads": "<p>Crowned Heads—founded by Jon Huber with partners including Espinosa alumnae—has become one of the most celebrated boutique brands of the 2010s. Core production takes place at <a href=\"/node/myfather/\">My Father</a> in Estelí, with historical ties to <a href=\"/node/nacsa/\">NACSA</a> for select projects.</p>\n<p>Lines such as Jericho Hill, Four Kicks, La Imperiosa, and Mule Kick showcase Nicaraguan power with boutique storytelling. Crowned Heads connects the My Father manufacturing powerhouse to the independent brand tier that helped redefine premium cigars after the Cuban embargo era.</p>",
  "southerndraw": "<p>Southern Draw Cigars—founded by Robert and Sharon Holt—is a family boutique brand with core production at <a href=\"/node/plasenciahonduras/\">El Paraíso (Plasencia Honduras)</a>. Lines such as Rose of Sharon, Kudzu, Jacob's Ladder, and Firethorn deliver approachable yet flavorful profiles that reflect the Holts' hospitality-driven brand ethos.</p>\n<p>Southern Draw also appears in STG Estelí's contract portfolio for certain lines, illustrating how even focused boutique brands can span multiple facilities as portfolios grow. The Plasencia Honduras link is the brand's primary manufacturing anchor on the map.</p>",
  "kristoff": "<p>Kristoff—founded by Lissette Perez-Carrillo—is a Dominican brand with production at <a href=\"/node/williamventura/\">Tabacalera William Ventura</a> and other DR facilities. Lines such as Original Maduro, GC Signature, Shiro, and Kristania offer consistent construction and approachable pricing within the premium segment.</p>\n<p>Kristoff connects William Ventura's contract ecosystem to a brand with its own identity—sharing manufacturing DNA with Viaje, Caldwell, and La Palina without sharing their blending vision.</p>",
  "montecristonc": "<p>Montecristo (Non-Cuban) is a heritage-name brand in <a href=\"/node/stg/\">Scandinavian Tobacco Group</a>'s portfolio, sold through <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a>. Significant Nicaraguan production takes place at <a href=\"/node/stgesteli/\">STG Estelí</a>—entirely separate from the iconic Cuban Montecristo line.</p>\n<p>The non-Cuban Montecristo illustrates how historic brand names migrate across political boundaries and corporate ownership structures, channeling consumer recognition toward accessible Caribbean and Central American production.</p>",
  "ryjnc": "<p>Romeo y Julieta (Non-Cuban) carries one of the most recognized names in cigars into the modern STG portfolio, with Nicaraguan production at <a href=\"/node/stgesteli/\">STG Estelí</a> and additional contract work through <a href=\"/node/plasencia/\">Plasencia</a>. Sold via <a href=\"/node/generalcigar/\">General Cigar</a>, the brand is wholly separate from Habanos S.A.'s Cuban Romeo y Julieta.</p>\n<p>For the ownership map, Romeo y Julieta (NC) is a clear example of how embargo-era name licensing created parallel supply chains that continue to thrive decades later.</p>",
  "fratello": "<p>Fratello—founded by Omar de Frias—is a boutique brand with dual production: <a href=\"/node/lazona/\">La Zona</a> in Estelí and <a href=\"/node/laisla/\">Tabacalera La Isla</a> in the Dominican Republic. Lines such as Classico, Navetta, Bianco, and Arlequin span medium to full profiles with excellent construction.</p>\n<p>Fratello's multi-factory strategy matches each blend to the right country and facility—a pattern increasingly common among serious boutique brands that outgrow a single production partner.</p>",
  "padilla": "<p>Padilla Cigars—led by Ernesto Padilla—distributes boutique Nicaraguan blends with production at <a href=\"/node/tabsa/\">TABSA</a>, <a href=\"/node/plasenciahonduras/\">Plasencia Honduras</a>, and <a href=\"/node/stgesteli/\">STG Estelí</a>. The brand connects three of the map's most important contract nodes, reflecting how negociant blenders source capacity across factories as lines evolve.</p>\n<p>Padilla sits alongside Illusione and Viaje as a TABSA regular while also leveraging Plasencia's Honduran expertise and STG's corporate-scale Estelí floor for select releases.</p>",
  "ozgener": "<p>Ozgener Family Cigars—Tim and Emre Ozgener—continues a family cigar legacy at <a href=\"/node/lacorona/\">La Corona Factory</a> in Estelí. Lines such as Bosphorus, Aramas, Cypher, and Pi showcase Nicaraguan tobacco with the Ozgener family's blending philosophy and design sensibility.</p>\n<p>Ozgener represents the boutique-to-vertical path: building a dedicated factory rather than relying indefinitely on anonymous contract production—a growing trend among established independent brands.</p>",
  "jassumkral": "<p>Jas Sum Kral is a boutique brand produced at <a href=\"/node/myfather/\">My Father</a> in Estelí—joining Crowned Heads, La Aroma de Cuba, and San Cristóbal in the García family's contract portfolio. Lines such as Red Knight, La Bomba, Fenix, and Kral deliver bold Nicaraguan character with boutique presentation.</p>\n<p>The My Father link places Jas Sum Kral in elite manufacturing company: the same factory that rolls Tatuaje and some of the industry's highest-rated Nicaraguan puros.</p>",
  "stolenthrone": "<p>Stolen Throne is a boutique brand associated with the <a href=\"/node/rojasfactory/\">Tabacalera New Order</a> / Rojas factory cluster in Estelí—part of the collaborative ecosystem around <a href=\"/node/noelrojas/\">Noel Rojas</a> and experimental Estelí projects.</p>\n<p>Stolen Throne exemplifies Estelí's partnership-driven factory culture, where blenders and factory operators co-create brands that thrive on collaboration rather than corporate scale.</p>",
  "deadwood": "<p>Deadwood is a Drew Estate line—Fat Bottom Betty, Sweet Jane, Yummy Bitches—produced at <a href=\"/node/raicescubanas/\">Raíces Cubanas</a> in Nicaragua rather than the company's flagship <a href=\"/node/lagranfabrica/\">La Gran Fábrica</a>. The line's distinctive branding and blend approach set it apart from Liga Privada and Undercrown.</p>\n<p>Deadwood shows how even a vertically integrated giant like <a href=\"/node/drewestate/\">Drew Estate</a> routes select projects through partner factories when the production culture or capacity demands it.</p>",
  "leafbyoscar": "<p>Leaf by Oscar is Oscar Valladares' candela-wrapped line—produced at <a href=\"/node/laflordecopan/\">La Flor de Copán</a> in Honduras. The distinctive outer leaf presentation and approachable blends helped define Oscar's brand identity in the boutique segment.</p>\n<p>Leaf by Oscar connects the Honduran production node to a creative packaging concept that stands out in a market often dominated by traditional band and box aesthetics.</p>",
  "oscarvalladares": "<p>Oscar Valladares is a Honduran boutique brand encompassing Super Fly, 2012, Island Jim, The Oscar, and related lines—with production tied to <a href=\"/node/laflordecopan/\">La Flor de Copán</a> and the broader Oscar factory network in Honduras.</p>\n<p>Oscar Valladares brought fresh energy to the Honduran boutique tier, complementing legacy Corojo brands like <a href=\"/node/camacho/\">Camacho</a> with creative vitolas and bold presentation.</p>",
  "mayflower": "<p>Mayflower Cigars was launched by Michael Knowles and is produced at the <a href=\"/node/oliva/\">Oliva</a> factory (<a href=\"/node/tabolisa/\">Tabolisa</a>) in Estelí, Nicaragua. The brand leverages Oliva's manufacturing excellence and tobacco access to deliver consistent, well-constructed cigars at competitive price points—benefiting from the same production infrastructure behind Serie V and Melanio without carrying the Oliva name on the band.</p>\n<p>Mayflower illustrates the contract manufacturing model at Oliva's scale: a blender with a vision tapping one of Estelí's largest facilities to execute production. For the map, it connects an independent brand identity to Oliva's industrial backbone—a common pattern for entrepreneurs who prioritize blend quality over factory ownership.</p>",
  "neworder": "<p>New Order of the Ages (NOA) originated as a collaborative factory and brand project led by <a href=\"/node/noelrojas/\">Noel Rojas</a>, with ties to the broader Renegade Cigars ecosystem in Estelí. The blends continue under the Rojas umbrella with primary manufacturing at <a href=\"/node/sanlotano/\">A.J. Fernandez</a> facilities—connecting NOA to one of Nicaragua's premier production operations.</p>\n<p>NOA sits alongside <a href=\"/node/guayacan/\">Guayacan</a> and the broader <a href=\"/node/rojas/\">Rojas Cigars</a> portfolio as part of Noel Rojas's expanding influence in the boutique scene. The project represents the collaborative, experimental spirit of Estelí's factory culture—where blenders, factory owners, and creative partnerships produce brands that might not exist in a more rigid, corporate-only landscape.</p>",
};
